1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,660
 Hypertext Transfer Protocol is the protocol

2
00:00:03,660 --> 00:00:05,560
 that browsers use to talk to servers.

3
00:00:05,560 --> 00:00:07,980
 Now we've used it for all kinds of other things

4
00:00:07,980 --> 00:00:10,740
 because it turns out that it's a super simple

5
00:00:10,740 --> 00:00:12,760
 and super elegant protocol.

6
00:00:12,760 --> 00:00:14,960
 Now this goes to a long time ago.

7
00:00:14,960 --> 00:00:17,660
 This protocol was invented in 1990,

8
00:00:17,660 --> 00:00:21,920
 which is like going on 30 years ago.

9
00:00:21,920 --> 00:00:24,380
 Yeah, going on 30 years ago now or more.

10
00:00:24,380 --> 00:00:28,040
 And there were many protocols.

11
00:00:28,040 --> 00:00:30,560
 You would have one piece of software

12
00:00:30,560 --> 00:00:32,500
 and there was server software and client software.

13
00:00:32,500 --> 00:00:34,200
 You had to match them up and then you'd talk

14
00:00:34,200 --> 00:00:36,640
 to the right port with this server software.

15
00:00:36,640 --> 00:00:38,880
 And one of the inventions of Tim Berners-Lee

16
00:00:38,880 --> 00:00:42,780
 and Robert Caillou at CERN was that we came up

17
00:00:42,780 --> 00:00:46,500
 with this notion of instead of lots of pieces of software,

18
00:00:46,500 --> 00:00:49,440
 we would have one piece of software called the web browser

19
00:00:49,440 --> 00:00:52,120
 and it would be multi-protocol.

20
00:00:52,120 --> 00:00:53,960
 And so we have this thing called the URL

21
00:00:53,960 --> 00:00:55,160
 or Uniform Resource Locator.

22
00:00:55,160 --> 00:00:58,400
 And we just sling these around, we just use them.

23
00:00:58,400 --> 00:01:01,960
 But these things, this was itself an amazing innovation

24
00:01:01,960 --> 00:01:04,400
 in 1990 'cause in the old days it'd be like,

25
00:01:04,400 --> 00:01:07,640
 use this piece of software and talk to this address.

26
00:01:07,640 --> 00:01:11,780
 So the URL captured three really important,

27
00:01:11,780 --> 00:01:12,800
 very separate things.

28
00:01:12,800 --> 00:01:16,060
 The first thing it did is it allowed for multiple protocols.

29
00:01:16,060 --> 00:01:19,680
 Now the one that you mostly have seen is HTTP or HTTPS,

30
00:01:19,680 --> 00:01:23,040
 that's a protocol, FTP colon or mail to colon

31
00:01:23,040 --> 00:01:25,040
 might be the other ones that you've seen.

32
00:01:25,040 --> 00:01:27,920
 And then a host and then a document.

33
00:01:27,920 --> 00:01:29,560
 And that host is a domain name,

34
00:01:29,560 --> 00:01:34,560
 which is a nice symbolic way to get a server address.

35
00:01:34,560 --> 00:01:38,400
 And that eventually resolves to an IP address

36
00:01:38,400 --> 00:01:42,160
 like 141.206.14.22 or something.

37
00:01:42,160 --> 00:01:43,960
 And then the document within that server

38
00:01:43,960 --> 00:01:47,720
 and that /page1.htm is the document in the server.

39
00:01:47,720 --> 00:01:50,520
 And I'm just saying before 1990,

40
00:01:50,520 --> 00:01:53,360
 there were many protocols and we did many things.

41
00:01:53,360 --> 00:01:57,400
 But after 1990, this one protocol, HTTP,

42
00:01:57,400 --> 00:02:01,100
 found its way into so many awesome solutions

43
00:02:01,100 --> 00:02:03,040
 that it's by far, other than email,

44
00:02:03,040 --> 00:02:05,880
 the dominant protocol that we use on the internet.

45
00:02:05,880 --> 00:02:09,400
 Like I said, it was invented at CERN

46
00:02:09,400 --> 00:02:11,040
 by Tim Berners-Lee and Robert Caillou

47
00:02:11,040 --> 00:02:13,040
 to retrieve documents and images.

48
00:02:13,040 --> 00:02:15,080
 And as soon as they built it,

49
00:02:15,080 --> 00:02:17,340
 because it was all the other protocols that came,

50
00:02:17,340 --> 00:02:19,680
 most of the other protocols were kind of complex

51
00:02:19,680 --> 00:02:21,860
 because we're computer scientists

52
00:02:21,860 --> 00:02:23,000
 and we make complex things.

53
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:24,240
 And we love complex things.

54
00:02:24,240 --> 00:02:27,460
 And we're very, very good at complex things.

55
00:02:27,460 --> 00:02:31,040
 But this was, when the web was being built,

56
00:02:31,040 --> 00:02:34,480
 Tim and Robert were not like,

57
00:02:34,480 --> 00:02:36,400
 we're gonna make the greatest thing ever.

58
00:02:36,400 --> 00:02:38,480
 We're just gonna make a simple thing.

59
00:02:38,480 --> 00:02:40,200
 So they made a simple thing,

60
00:02:40,200 --> 00:02:41,800
 but it turned out to be the greatest thing ever

61
00:02:41,800 --> 00:02:44,880
 because different engineers would be like,

62
00:02:44,880 --> 00:02:47,680
 oh wow, I can use that a little different way.

63
00:02:47,680 --> 00:02:50,200
 And the grounding of it was super simple.

64
00:02:50,200 --> 00:02:53,040
 And the basic concept was you connect to a server,

65
00:02:53,040 --> 00:02:54,040
 you figure out where it is,

66
00:02:54,040 --> 00:02:57,840
 you send a single command with a bit of extra data,

67
00:02:57,840 --> 00:03:00,480
 and then you get back something, a document.

68
00:03:00,480 --> 00:03:03,960
 It could be an image, it could be data, it could be HTML.

69
00:03:03,960 --> 00:03:06,960
 And it was really amazing, right?

70
00:03:06,960 --> 00:03:09,920
 And so the sockets, the underlying sockets

71
00:03:09,920 --> 00:03:11,760
 are the things that make the phone call.

72
00:03:11,760 --> 00:03:16,300
 HTTP is what we do once this phone call has been established.

73
00:03:17,760 --> 00:03:20,720
 So one of the things that made the internet so successful

74
00:03:20,720 --> 00:03:23,680
 starting in the 1960s was a radical openness,

75
00:03:23,680 --> 00:03:27,800
 a very, we're all around the same campfire feeling,

76
00:03:27,800 --> 00:03:31,760
 very friendly, respectful, that still allowed criticism.

77
00:03:31,760 --> 00:03:35,240
 There wasn't like one super genius that designed this

78
00:03:35,240 --> 00:03:36,600
 or one company that designed this.

79
00:03:36,600 --> 00:03:38,320
 This was a collaboration.

80
00:03:38,320 --> 00:03:40,840
 And the collaboration was around a set of open standards

81
00:03:40,840 --> 00:03:42,640
 and meetings to help build these standards.

82
00:03:42,640 --> 00:03:44,580
 And they were called RFCs.

83
00:03:44,580 --> 00:03:46,720
 They were called Request for Comments.

84
00:03:46,720 --> 00:03:48,560
 And there was a group that built these

85
00:03:48,560 --> 00:03:51,680
 called the Internet Engineering Task Force, the IETF.

86
00:03:51,680 --> 00:03:55,720
 And the Request for Comments is a fun notion.

87
00:03:55,720 --> 00:03:58,400
 We're looking here at a September 1981 document,

88
00:03:58,400 --> 00:04:02,680
 which is 40 years old about now,

89
00:04:02,680 --> 00:04:04,600
 and it's called Request for Comments.

90
00:04:04,600 --> 00:04:09,160
 And the idea is as engineers, we might have a design

91
00:04:09,160 --> 00:04:12,000
 that everyone thinks is the greatest thing ever,

92
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:14,560
 but we should always question.

93
00:04:14,560 --> 00:04:18,320
 No design is perfect, no design is beyond question,

94
00:04:18,320 --> 00:04:21,040
 no design is beyond commentary.

95
00:04:21,040 --> 00:04:26,000
 And so even when they're 40 years old and used worldwide,

96
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:29,240
 and dang amazing, we still say

97
00:04:29,240 --> 00:04:30,560
 there is room for improvement.

98
00:04:30,560 --> 00:04:35,000
 And so this talks about, I think this one is IP,

99
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:36,660
 and there's an IPv6.

100
00:04:36,660 --> 00:04:39,160
 There's another one, if you look for this RFC

101
00:04:39,160 --> 00:04:41,360
 that we're looking at here, there'd be IPv6,

102
00:04:41,360 --> 00:04:42,280
 and you'd start reading it.

103
00:04:42,280 --> 00:04:45,240
 And it's pretty dense reading, but as an engineer,

104
00:04:45,240 --> 00:04:47,720
 it gives you all the details to build a router

105
00:04:47,720 --> 00:04:50,080
 or build a piece of software or build whatever.

106
00:04:50,080 --> 00:04:53,760
 And these are 100% public documents.

107
00:04:53,760 --> 00:04:56,680
 And the idea was is that no company,

108
00:04:56,680 --> 00:04:59,400
 because literally the companies that were around in 1960,

109
00:04:59,400 --> 00:05:04,160
 if they had said Burroughs or Sperry owns the internet

110
00:05:04,160 --> 00:05:06,080
 or digital equipment owns the internet,

111
00:05:06,080 --> 00:05:07,880
 they're all out of business

112
00:05:07,880 --> 00:05:09,880
 because they didn't make good choices,

113
00:05:09,880 --> 00:05:11,640
 but the market was able to make good choices.

114
00:05:11,640 --> 00:05:15,000
 And because the commons were these open standards

115
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:18,800
 and open specifications, new companies like Sun Microsystems

116
00:05:18,800 --> 00:05:21,820
 and new operating systems like Linux could come in,

117
00:05:21,820 --> 00:05:23,720
 and even Windows could come in

118
00:05:23,720 --> 00:05:25,460
 and participate as full participants

119
00:05:25,460 --> 00:05:27,400
 'cause they just read these specs

120
00:05:27,400 --> 00:05:28,640
 and all of a sudden they're interoperating

121
00:05:28,640 --> 00:05:29,480
 with everybody else.

122
00:05:29,480 --> 00:05:32,840
 This is fundamental and foundational

123
00:05:32,840 --> 00:05:33,800
 to how the internet works.

124
00:05:33,800 --> 00:05:36,500
 And I'm not saying you're supposed to go read them,

125
00:05:36,500 --> 00:05:38,580
 but it's just fascinating to understand

126
00:05:38,580 --> 00:05:41,100
 that the entire technological infrastructure

127
00:05:41,100 --> 00:05:43,820
 upon which the internet is built is free,

128
00:05:43,820 --> 00:05:47,660
 license free, royalty free,

129
00:05:47,660 --> 00:05:52,400
 and you could build a brand new gadget

130
00:05:52,400 --> 00:05:54,160
 and you could hook it to the internet

131
00:05:54,160 --> 00:05:55,480
 by reading these specifications.

132
00:05:55,480 --> 00:05:57,960
 You don't have to pay a developer's license or nothing.

133
00:05:57,960 --> 00:06:00,040
 It's, dang, it's cool.

134
00:06:00,040 --> 00:06:02,880
 Sorry, I'm just a little bit too excited about that.

135
00:06:02,880 --> 00:06:06,520
 So let's take a look at one of these in particular.

136
00:06:06,520 --> 00:06:08,880
 Now this is probably supplanted,

137
00:06:08,880 --> 00:06:10,800
 but we'll look at RFC 2616.

138
00:06:10,800 --> 00:06:12,060
 They go up in numbers.

139
00:06:12,060 --> 00:06:16,560
 And so this is HTTP,

140
00:06:16,560 --> 00:06:19,880
 Hypertext Transfer Protocol.

141
00:06:19,880 --> 00:06:23,360
 And if you wanted to build a web browser or a web server,

142
00:06:23,360 --> 00:06:24,960
 you could read this document.

143
00:06:24,960 --> 00:06:27,280
 Go ahead, read the document.

144
00:06:27,280 --> 00:06:29,720
 And if you read down far enough, you'll say,

145
00:06:29,720 --> 00:06:32,680
 "Oh, this is how you make a request."

146
00:06:32,680 --> 00:06:34,200
 Blah, blah, blah, it's got a header

147
00:06:34,200 --> 00:06:36,020
 and it's got like a carriage return line feed

148
00:06:36,020 --> 00:06:37,540
 and then a message body,

149
00:06:37,540 --> 00:06:40,440
 and you gotta do this and this is what it looks like.

150
00:06:40,440 --> 00:06:42,040
 And this is how it works, right?

151
00:06:42,040 --> 00:06:44,520
 And so at some point you're deep in this document

152
00:06:44,520 --> 00:06:47,160
 and you're finding out in this page right here

153
00:06:47,160 --> 00:06:51,200
 of this document how your browser is supposed to format it.

154
00:06:51,200 --> 00:06:54,080
 And this tells both the client and the server

155
00:06:54,080 --> 00:06:56,940
 what the rules of the protocol are.

156
00:06:56,940 --> 00:07:00,280
 Now, it's a lot easier to just for me to tell you.

157
00:07:00,280 --> 00:07:03,100
 So you connect to the server on a socket,

158
00:07:03,100 --> 00:07:06,120
 usually port 80 or port 443.

159
00:07:06,120 --> 00:07:11,120
 And then the client is supposed to make the first sound.

160
00:07:11,120 --> 00:07:14,140
 It makes first request.

161
00:07:14,140 --> 00:07:17,840
 It sends a line for the carriage return line feed at the end

162
00:07:17,840 --> 00:07:19,980
 that has the characters, there are other ones,

163
00:07:19,980 --> 00:07:24,520
 but get get space, a URL space, and then a protocol.

164
00:07:24,520 --> 00:07:26,800
 And right now I'm using this HTTP 1.0

165
00:07:26,800 --> 00:07:29,360
 because I can do it by hand, right?

166
00:07:29,360 --> 00:07:32,020
 And so you ask for a document

167
00:07:32,020 --> 00:07:35,860
 and then you can optionally send some header information,

168
00:07:35,860 --> 00:07:38,040
 things like what language this browser,

169
00:07:38,040 --> 00:07:39,920
 person that this browser prefers,

170
00:07:39,920 --> 00:07:43,760
 what are the capabilities of this browser,

171
00:07:43,760 --> 00:07:44,840
 what version browser we have.

172
00:07:44,840 --> 00:07:47,120
 So there's a series of things you say, give me this document

173
00:07:47,120 --> 00:07:48,460
 and here's something about the browser

174
00:07:48,460 --> 00:07:50,080
 that's requesting the document,

175
00:07:50,080 --> 00:07:52,920
 including information like cookies that are being said.

176
00:07:52,920 --> 00:07:57,120
 Now, so in case you wanna know who is doing this request

177
00:07:57,120 --> 00:07:59,080
 because you've logged somebody in and set a cookie

178
00:07:59,080 --> 00:08:00,720
 to indicate that they're logged in,

179
00:08:00,720 --> 00:08:02,640
 that's all sent on this get request.

180
00:08:02,640 --> 00:08:04,600
 What will not send the headers,

181
00:08:04,600 --> 00:08:07,600
 there's actually incoming headers and then outgoing headers.

182
00:08:07,600 --> 00:08:10,160
 We'll see these when we start looking at

183
00:08:10,160 --> 00:08:12,040
 Firefox's debugging console.

184
00:08:12,040 --> 00:08:16,840
 And so this is an entire interaction

185
00:08:16,840 --> 00:08:18,680
 that you can do on your laptop.

186
00:08:18,680 --> 00:08:20,600
 Now, I'm not gonna do it for you,

187
00:08:20,600 --> 00:08:25,160
 but I would note that the program Telnet that this uses

188
00:08:25,160 --> 00:08:28,500
 has been removed from most computers, it makes me sad.

189
00:08:28,500 --> 00:08:29,960
 They think of it as a security hole

190
00:08:29,960 --> 00:08:32,080
 'cause it doesn't use encrypted connections,

191
00:08:32,080 --> 00:08:36,000
 like port 80 is not an encrypted connection.

192
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:40,000
 But ultimately, you can install,

193
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:42,240
 go search on your favorite search engine

194
00:08:42,240 --> 00:08:44,280
 and find out how to install Telnet.

195
00:08:44,280 --> 00:08:45,580
 But if you get in a command line,

196
00:08:45,580 --> 00:08:47,720
 whether it's a Windows command line

197
00:08:47,720 --> 00:08:50,740
 or a Mac command line or a Linux command line,

198
00:08:50,740 --> 00:08:53,180
 and you get Telnet properly installed,

199
00:08:53,180 --> 00:08:55,580
 you can type the following command,

200
00:08:55,580 --> 00:09:00,580
 telnet datapr4e.org 80 and then hit enter.

201
00:09:01,200 --> 00:09:02,320
 And at that point,

202
00:09:02,320 --> 00:09:05,200
 so Telnet originally was used to log into computers,

203
00:09:05,200 --> 00:09:07,400
 but if the server we're talking to

204
00:09:07,400 --> 00:09:09,180
 and the protocol that we're talking to is simple enough,

205
00:09:09,180 --> 00:09:11,940
 and in this case, HTTP/1 is simple enough

206
00:09:11,940 --> 00:09:13,900
 for us to be able to do this,

207
00:09:13,900 --> 00:09:15,600
 we're actually talking to the server

208
00:09:15,600 --> 00:09:18,840
 'cause I remember I said that these are applications,

209
00:09:18,840 --> 00:09:21,660
 they're not, your browser is not talking to files,

210
00:09:21,660 --> 00:09:24,040
 your browser is talking to an application on a server

211
00:09:24,040 --> 00:09:26,320
 and the server might give you back a file.

212
00:09:26,320 --> 00:09:28,360
 So it's really talking to a piece of software

213
00:09:28,360 --> 00:09:31,920
 and we'll see this in more detail in the next section.

214
00:09:31,920 --> 00:09:35,400
 And so what'll happen is because the HTTP protocol

215
00:09:35,400 --> 00:09:39,800
 requires that the client speak first, we have to type.

216
00:09:39,800 --> 00:09:42,960
 Now, if you can get this working and type wrong things

217
00:09:42,960 --> 00:09:46,080
 and type a couple of enters, new lines,

218
00:09:46,080 --> 00:09:48,280
 you will see that you're talking to a piece of software

219
00:09:48,280 --> 00:09:51,320
 and it will say, you have violated my protocol.

220
00:09:51,320 --> 00:09:54,280
 You're not talking to a thing that has any online help

221
00:09:54,280 --> 00:09:56,320
 or user interface or anything like that.

222
00:09:56,320 --> 00:09:58,560
 You're talking to a server and your job

223
00:09:58,560 --> 00:10:00,960
 is to request some data using the proper format

224
00:10:00,960 --> 00:10:03,360
 because you read the specifications

225
00:10:03,360 --> 00:10:05,920
 about the proper format, right?

226
00:10:05,920 --> 00:10:07,720
 So in this particular one, we just,

227
00:10:07,720 --> 00:10:08,920
 it's easier to cut and paste this

228
00:10:08,920 --> 00:10:11,040
 'cause some of these servers, if you don't type fast enough,

