00:11:25,120 --> 00:11:26,560
 on how, what that works.

263
00:11:26,560 --> 00:11:29,680
 But for example, 200 means that you got a document.

264
00:11:29,680 --> 00:11:31,680
 Another one that you might've seen is 404.

265
00:11:31,680 --> 00:11:33,680
 It might say 404 not found.

266
00:11:33,680 --> 00:11:35,720
 So if you go to a webpage and it doesn't exist,

267
00:11:35,720 --> 00:11:38,560
 something will say 404 in your browser usually

268
00:11:38,560 --> 00:11:41,520
 unless it says here's a search box, go find it.

269
00:11:41,520 --> 00:11:45,000
 But you can, there's a status and so you might,

270
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:46,320
 the thing that you're typing,

271
00:11:46,320 --> 00:11:49,800
 page1.htm may or may not be on this server.

272
00:11:49,800 --> 00:11:53,280
 If it is, then you'll get a 200 okay and the data

273
00:11:53,280 --> 00:11:55,560
 or you'll get a 404 not found.

274
00:11:55,560 --> 00:11:58,880
 And then we get some response data, some header response.

275
00:11:58,880 --> 00:12:00,680
 And this header response looks pretty much

276
00:12:00,680 --> 00:12:03,160
 like the same format of the data we would have sent

277
00:12:03,160 --> 00:12:05,760
 into the browser if we were sending things

278
00:12:05,760 --> 00:12:06,840
 like that in there.

279
00:12:06,840 --> 00:12:11,480
 Here it's what the date is, what the server we're using,

280
00:12:11,480 --> 00:12:14,720
 last modified and one of the important things

281
00:12:14,720 --> 00:12:18,080
 is what kind of content are you about to see.

282
00:12:18,080 --> 00:12:20,720
 Content type in this case is tech/html

283
00:12:20,720 --> 00:12:22,520
 which means the thing coming next.

284
00:12:22,520 --> 00:12:25,280
 And then there's a blank line and the blank line

285
00:12:25,280 --> 00:12:28,480
 is our indication as we're reading this data

286
00:12:28,480 --> 00:12:31,120
 that we've finished the header which is really metadata

287
00:12:31,120 --> 00:12:34,240
 about the page we're retrieving and the actual page itself.

288
00:12:34,240 --> 00:12:37,760
 And so the rest of this page is the actual data

289
00:12:37,760 --> 00:12:39,400
 and we know the format of it

290
00:12:39,400 --> 00:12:42,400
 because we were told before the page starts.

291
00:12:42,400 --> 00:12:46,040
 This could be image/png, this could be XML,

292
00:12:46,040 --> 00:12:48,760
 the application/xml and it could be JSON,

293
00:12:48,760 --> 00:12:51,280
 it could be like anything and then the browser

294
00:12:51,280 --> 00:12:52,960
 is supposed to, and if this was an image,

295
00:12:52,960 --> 00:12:55,040
 it would be like garble, garble, garble,

296
00:12:55,040 --> 00:12:56,360
 garble, garble, garble, right?

297
00:12:56,360 --> 00:12:59,640
 It would be all garbled stuff that we can't really see

298
00:12:59,640 --> 00:13:02,640
 but the browser knows what a png or jpeg looks like

299
00:13:02,640 --> 00:13:07,640
 and it shows it to you and it basically uses this tech/html

300
00:13:07,640 --> 00:13:09,560
 to tell you what's going on.

301
00:13:09,560 --> 00:13:13,240
 And so this then, your browser has read all this information,

302
00:13:13,240 --> 00:13:15,440
 it has both the metadata and the data

303
00:13:15,440 --> 00:13:18,960
 about the retrieved page and then its job is to sort of

304
00:13:18,960 --> 00:13:22,520
 produce a pretty rendered version of the page

305
00:13:22,520 --> 00:13:24,000
 and show it to you.

306
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:26,760
 And that is the request recycle.

307
00:13:26,760 --> 00:13:28,480
 Again, you don't have to do this,

308
00:13:28,480 --> 00:13:30,520
 you can just sort of believe that it's done here

309
00:13:30,520 --> 00:13:32,760
 but if you want to install Telnet on your system,

310
00:13:32,760 --> 00:13:34,540
 it's not a bad thing to install Telnet,

311
00:13:34,540 --> 00:13:36,880
 it's kind of a classic fun thing.

312
00:13:36,880 --> 00:13:39,040
 It's far less useful than it was in the early days

313
00:13:39,040 --> 00:13:41,280
 'cause we used to use Telnet to test everything,

314
00:13:41,280 --> 00:13:43,320
 now we've got like browser developer consoles

315
00:13:43,320 --> 00:13:46,320
 that are way easier than Telnet.

316
00:13:46,320 --> 00:13:48,840
 But it's kind of a cool thing,

317
00:13:48,840 --> 00:13:50,680
 feel free to do this and you'll be like,

318
00:13:50,680 --> 00:13:54,000
 I know what's really going on.

319
00:13:54,000 --> 00:13:59,000
 And so I'm a big fan of using the console,

320
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:03,800
 of using the terminal, of using text-based interfaces,

321
00:14:03,800 --> 00:14:06,420
 I think they're actually way more accessible,

322
00:14:06,420 --> 00:14:07,840
 I think it's awesome.

323
00:14:07,840 --> 00:14:12,840
 And in a way, all these fancy graphical user interfaces

324
00:14:12,840 --> 00:14:17,000
 distract us from the simplicity of what's going on

325
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:18,340
 inside of computers 'cause you think,

326
00:14:18,340 --> 00:14:19,800
 well, where's the button?

327
00:14:19,800 --> 00:14:21,600
 And the answer is, oh, there's probably some command

328
00:14:21,600 --> 00:14:24,320
 inside this computer that does what the button does.

329
00:14:24,320 --> 00:14:26,520
 So I have a former student of mine

330
00:14:26,520 --> 00:14:30,300
 who actually wrote the scene

331
00:14:30,300 --> 00:14:33,320
 and I think maybe it was Matrix 2,

332
00:14:33,320 --> 00:14:36,840
 I think this was Matrix 2, yeah, Matrix Reloaded.

333
00:14:36,840 --> 00:14:40,760
 And this scene where Trinity is breaking into the power grid

334
00:14:40,760 --> 00:14:43,600
 and she is using the console.

335
00:14:43,600 --> 00:14:46,160
 And it turned out that the way this scene was written

336
00:14:46,160 --> 00:14:49,560
 is it was written exactly as a hacker,

337
00:14:49,560 --> 00:14:52,640
 whether that's a hacker with bad intent or good intent,

338
00:14:52,640 --> 00:14:54,320
 'cause there are hackers with good intent

339
00:14:54,320 --> 00:14:56,000
 who are trying to break into your system

340
00:14:56,000 --> 00:14:58,000
 so they can tell you for you pay them

341
00:14:58,000 --> 00:14:59,340
 to break into your system,

342
00:14:59,340 --> 00:15:01,600
 so that they can tell you your vulnerabilities.

343
00:15:01,600 --> 00:15:05,400
 But you can take a look at the analysis of this little scene

344
00:15:05,400 --> 00:15:09,500
 and this sort of is just one of the cool things

345
00:15:09,500 --> 00:15:13,200
 about me teaching people about how to use the command line

346
00:15:13,200 --> 00:15:15,560
 and increasingly me teaching people

347
00:15:15,560 --> 00:15:16,840
 about how to use Linux.

348
00:15:16,840 --> 00:15:20,200
 I really think that it's okay to know

349
00:15:20,200 --> 00:15:21,960
 your Mac and Windows command line,

350
00:15:21,960 --> 00:15:25,080
 but really increasingly the world and the server world

351
00:15:25,080 --> 00:15:27,560
 and we're starting to work on web servers in this class

352
00:15:27,560 --> 00:15:29,320
 and you might as well start learning some Linux

353
00:15:29,320 --> 00:15:31,720
 'cause that's an important skill,

354
00:15:31,720 --> 00:15:35,400
 just writing some Java code or Ruby code or Django code,

355
00:15:35,400 --> 00:15:38,000
 that's a skill, but knowing how to start the server,

356
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:41,380
 debug your application, find log files, et cetera,

357
00:15:41,380 --> 00:15:43,420
 in the command line is really important

358
00:15:43,420 --> 00:15:44,720
 in real production systems

359
00:15:44,720 --> 00:15:48,300
 'cause we're gonna play in some simplified environments

360
00:15:48,300 --> 00:15:50,200
 to make it a little easier,

361
00:15:50,200 --> 00:15:52,960
 but those simplified environments go away

362
00:15:52,960 --> 00:15:55,360
 once you go into real production in a real job

363
00:15:55,360 --> 00:15:59,280
 and so I'm really into teaching you Linux command line,

364
00:15:59,280 --> 00:16:01,200
 et cetera, et cetera.

365
00:16:01,200 --> 00:16:04,600
 So up next, we're going to show you in Python,

366
00:16:04,600 --> 00:16:08,260
 in effect, as few lines as I can possibly show you,

367
00:16:08,260 --> 00:16:12,280
 how a browser works, how a browser sends the HTTP protocol,

368
00:16:12,280 --> 00:16:14,640
 how a server reacts to the HTTP protocol

369
00:16:14,640 --> 00:16:17,680
 and returns documents, so that's what's coming up next.

